      "text": {
        "lat": "104.— His ab illo dictis delectatus Xerxes respondit: ‘Pythi, nullum adhuc, praeter te, hominum reperi talia offerentem. Tu vero magnifice me excepisti, et pecunias ingentes polliceris. Tibi ergo invicem ego dona haecce tribuo: in meorum hospitum numero te repono: do tibi etiam magnum auri pondus. Perge vero retinere quae acquisivisti, ac semper talem te virum praesta. Haec facientem, neque nunc, nec in posterum te poenitebit.’",
        "eng": "104.— Delighted by these words from him, Xerxes replied: ‘Pythius, I have found no man yet, besides you, offering such things. You have indeed received me splendidly, and promise vast sums of money. Therefore, in return, I bestow these gifts upon you: I place you in the number of my guests: I also give you a great weight of gold. Go on to keep what you have obtained, and always show yourself a man of such worth. Doing these, you will not be sorry now, nor in the future.’"
